               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-270-person1486">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WAKEFIELD
               <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1486" type="surname" value="WAKEFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1486" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1486" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a carman to Mr. Thomas Eddy. I was coming out of his place into Blenheim-mews on the 7th of April, and saw the prisoner go by with this bridle on his arm, which I knew was Mr. Eddy's, as I had been in the habit of putting it on the horse every day - I said to a person named Kitchen, "That man has got a bridle, and we had better go and take him," which we did- I have known him some time; I believe he had an honest character.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-270-person1487">
                  JOHN 
                  KITCHER
               <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1487" type="surname" value="KITCHER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1487" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1487" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of Mr. Thomas Eddy. At a quarter-past seven o'clock, we saw the prisoner go by with this bridle, and took him at the corner of Blenheim-street - he said he had bought it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-270-person1488">
                  ANGELIOUS 
                  BETRAUN
               <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1488" type="surname" value="BETRAUN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1488" type="given" value="ANGELIOUS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-270-person1488" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer, and took him.</p>


               <p>Prisoner's Defence. Necessity and poverty led me to take it. I had been to borrow 6d. of Mr. Eddy, and he was not in the way.</p>
               <p>
